Spatial Modeling


Motivation

We have studied a variety of data sets thus far that included observations of responses and accompanying predictors (i.e.covariates) for each response. We have ignored the fact that these observations must occur somewhere despite the fact that many, if not all, research problems in environmental and social science are inherently spatial. The usual layout for these data sets is that each row contains a response and predictor variables. Spatial data sets have these of course, but each row also contains geographic coordinates usually latitude and longitude or, better yet, UTM coordinates, giving each observation a specific location in space.

Why do we care? Remember a fundamental assumption of virtually all statistical modeling is that the residuals are independent and identically distributed:

\[\begin{align} y_i &= g(\theta, x_i)+\epsilon_{i} \\ \epsilon_{i} &\sim \textrm{normal}(0, \sigma^2) \end{align}\]

We have some deterministic model \(g(\theta, x_{i})\) that predicts an observation \(y_i\) with some error \(\epsilon_i\). The errors must be independent, which is to say that information about one \(\epsilon_{i}\) tells you nothing about another \(\epsilon_{i}\). Recall we can combine the likelihoods of individual observations into a total likelihood across an observation set by taking a product of the individual likelihoods, if we can assume independence. The assumption of independence means that the \(\boldsymbol{\epsilon}\)s must be independent.

It is often the case that observations that are close together in space are more similar than observations that are farther apart.This is not a problem if our model accounts for this relationship by the clever use of covariates, but sometimes covariates cannot account for all the spatial dependence in the data, leaving \(\boldsymbol{\epsilon}\)s that resemble their neighbors. This means that \(\boldsymbol{\epsilon}\)s that are close together are conditional, which is to say of course that information about one \(\epsilon\) informs us to some degree about its neighbors. Another way to express this conditional relationship is that \(\boldsymbol{\epsilon}\)s are autocorrelated. It is vital that you understand that this is different from auto correlation in the data, which will almost always be present at some scale.

The Bayesian framework does not flinch at autocorrelated \(\boldsymbol{\epsilon}\)s. We deal with spatially conditional residuals in precisely the same way we deal with all other unobserved quantities: we model them.

We have learned about two types of spatial data data like observations of soil moisture or disease prevalence arising from a continuous spatial process and data like average income or political affiliation that reflect an area a state, county, or precinct. We will focus on continuous spatial data here, but the approach is not dramatically different for areal data.

The best way to learn new modeling skills involves three steps:

1. Understand the math. Understand the math. Understand the math.

2. Simulate data so that you know the values of generating, unobserved quantities.

3. Write code to implement the mathematics using the simulated data.

Step 1 was handled in the lecture on spatial modeling and your deep thoughts about the topic. We will go through steps 23 in this problem.

Simulating data

You should work to understand what is going on from now on, with the exception of some of the plotting, which you can figure out at another time. We start by simulating some data with spatially structured standardized covariates and a response that lacks spatial dependence except the dependence created by the covariates. Study the code below. Especially take note of how the \(y\)s are simulated.

First we transform the coordinates in utgrid.locs to construct a spatially-explicit predictor \(x\). In addition we store the total number of UTM coordinates, ntot, found in utgrid.locs.

x = scale(utgrid.locs[, 1]) + scale(utgrid.locs[, 2])
dat = cbind(utgrid.locs, x)
colnames(dat) = c("easting", "northing", "x")
n <- dim(utgrid.locs)[1]

Dont worry about the transformation! - instead focus on the spatial patterning in \(x\) when we plot of each of their values on a map using their associated coordinates. It should be obvious that these predictors could give rise to spatially structured data.

image(matrix(dat[, 3], length(xg), length(yg)), x = xg, y = yg, main = "x",
      col = rev(rainbow(100, start = 0, end = .7)), xlab = "easting", ylab = "northing",
      cex.main = .8, cex.axis = .7, xlim = c(min(xg), max(xg)), ylim = c(min(yg), max(yg)))
points(ut.utm@coords, type = "l", lwd = 3)

Next we make an unstructured response variable. To do this, we make a design matrix with 2 columns and 875 rows, where the number of rows corresponds to the number of UTM coordinates. The first columns represents the intercept and is a vector of 1s and the second column is the \(x\)s.

X = matrix(c(rep(1, n), dat[,3]), n, 2, byrow = FALSE)

We define some \(\beta\) coefficients and a \(\sigma\). Then we simulate a vector of responses using a normal distribution. This is the same as making 875 draws from rnorm, one for each grid point, where \(\mu\) is a vector of means computed as the product of the design matrix \(X\) and the vector \(\beta\):

\[\begin{eqnarray} y_{i} &\sim& \textrm{normal}(\mu_{i}, \sigma^{2})\\ \mu_{i} & = & \boldsymbol{X}\times\boldsymbol{\beta} \end{eqnarray}\] 
beta = c(1, -2)
sigma = .5
y = rnorm(n, X%*%beta, sigma)
dat = as.data.frame(cbind(y, dat))

We have created a data frame called dat with one response, two covariates, and a shared spatial position for each observation in UTM. Data like this are usually where you will start.

Aspatial model

The goal of this exercise is to fit an aspatial model in JAGS predicting the response \(y\) as a linear function of the covariate \(x\). First model these data using the normal distribution and then compare the run time to that using the multivariate normal. These models are equivalent but the former will run much faster since computation time increases as the square of the number of data points (what causes this to occur in the multivariate normal implementation?).

Here is the joint distribution using the multivariate normal:

\[\begin{align} \big[\beta_{1}, \beta_{2}, \sigma \mid \mathbf{y}\big] & \propto \textrm{multivariate normal}\big(\mathbf{y} \mid \boldsymbol{\mu},\sigma^{2}I\big) \textrm{normal}\big(\beta_{1} \mid 0, 1E5 \big) \textrm{normal}\big(\beta_{2} \mid 0, 1E5 \big) \textrm{uniform}\big(\sigma \mid 0, 10\big)\\ \boldsymbol{\mu}&=\mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta} \end{align}\]

The second argument to the multivariate normal is a variance covariance matrix, which in this case is simply a matrix with \(\sigma^2\) on the diagonal and zeros elsewhere:

\[\sigma^{2}I = \sigma^2 \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 & \dots & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 & \dots & 0 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \dots & 1 \end{bmatrix}_{\,\,875\times 875} = \begin{bmatrix} \sigma^{2} & 0 & 0 & \dots & 0 \\ 0 & \sigma^{2} & 0 & \dots & 0 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \dots & \sigma^{2} \end{bmatrix}_{\,\,875 \times 875} \]


1. How did I determine the dimensions of the identity matrix?


875 is the total number of coordinates in utgrid.locs which corresponds to the number of observations in your model. You have already calculated this value and stored it in n. The identity matrix is square since it includes the covariance between each of the residuals.


Spatial models take a long time to run so a useful way to work is to subset the data to reduce the number of points and use a small number of iterations until you get some reasonable if not perfect results. Then increase the size of the data set and the number of iterations. The code below will be helpful in doing that. Ir starts by keeping 20% of the data and uses a small number of iterations for a single chain. We plot the predictor and label all the data points we selected for our model with black circles. We do this simply to make sure that our random draw of samples has pretty even spatial coverage prior to fitting.

n.adapt = 500
n.update = 1000
n.iter = 1000
k = sort(sample(1:n, round(0.2 * n)))

inits = list(
  list(
    beta = c(.8, -.8),
    sigma = .02
  )
)

data = list(
  y = as.double(dat$y[k]),
  X = X[k,],
  k = length(k)
)

image(matrix(dat[, 4], length(xg), length(yg)), x = xg, y = yg, main = "x",
      col = rev(rainbow(100, start = 0, end = .7)), xlab = "easting", ylab = "northing",
      cex.main = .8, cex.axis = .7, xlim = c(min(xg), max(xg)), ylim = c(min(yg), max(yg)))
points(utgrid.locs[k,], pch = 20, cex = .8)


2. Time to write the model using the normal distribution. Use the priors we provide above to save time and remember it is critical that your code contains a derived quantity for the residuals, i.e., \(\epsilon_i=y_i-\mu_i\). Include code for a posterior predictive check for the coefficient of variation.


{ # Extra bracket needed only for R markdown files
sink("AspatialJAGSNormal.R")
cat("
model{
  # priors
  for (i in 1:2){
    beta[i] ~ dnorm(0, .00001)
  }
  sigma ~ dunif(0, 10)
  tau <- 1/sigma^2

  # likelihood
  mu <- X %*% beta
  for (i in 1:k){
    y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau)
    y.new[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau)
    epsilon[i] <- y[i] - mu[i]
  }

  # derived quantities
  cv.y <- sd(y[]) / mean(y[])
  cv.y.new <- sd(y.new[]) / mean(y.new[])
  pvalue.cv <- step(cv.y.new - cv.y)   

}
", fill = TRUE)
sink()
} # Extra bracket needed only for R markdown files


3. Run the model in JAGS with a single chain. How would we assess convergence with just one chain?


We can use the the Heidelberger and Welch diagnostic to assess convergence for a single chain, which can be useful during early stages of model development before you have initialized multiple chains. The diagnostic tests for stationary in the distribution and also tests if the mean of the distribution is accurately estimated. For details go to ?heidel.diag. We can be confident of convergence if all parameters pass the test for stationarity and half width mean. We can also plot the chain and look at it to see if it looks stationary.

jm_a = jags.model("AspatialJAGSNormal.R", n.adapt = n.adapt, n.chains = 1, inits = inits, data = data)
## Compiling model graph
##    Resolving undeclared variables
##    Allocating nodes
## Graph information:
##    Observed stochastic nodes: 175
##    Unobserved stochastic nodes: 178
##    Total graph size: 1079
## 
## Initializing model
update(jm_a, n.iter = n.update)
zm1 = coda.samples(jm_a, variable.names = c("beta", "sigma", "epsilon", "mu", "pvalue.cv"), n.iter = n.iter)
heidel.diag(zm1[, c(1, 2, (length(k) * 2 + 4))])
## [[1]]
##                                       
##         Stationarity start     p-value

plot(zm1[, c(1, 2, (length(k) * 2 + 4))])

The estimated values are pretty close to the generating values of \(\beta_{1} = 1\), \(\beta_{2} = -2\), and \(\sigma = 0.5\). They are off somewhat for two reasons - the data are a realization from these generating values and we randomly subset our data prior to fitting the model. 6. Assess the spatial independence of the residual means using a variogram. A variogram is a plot of the correlation between residuals as a function of spatial distance. First subset dat to include only the 875 points for which you have a model residual. Use the coordinates function in the gstats package to convert the new data frame to a SpatialPointsDataFrame. Then use the variogram function to calculate the semivariance as a function of distance. Plot this. Does it look like the residuals are spatially correlated? Think back to lecture.


dat2 <- dat[k,]
coordinates(dat2) = ~easting + northing
variogramUtah = variogram(epsilon ~ 1, dat2)

8. Re code the model using a multivariate normal and repeat this exercise. Compare your results. Notice, you will need to give JAGS an identity matrix \(I\) as data this time.


{ # Extra bracket needed only for R markdown files
sink("AspatialJAGS.R")
cat("
model{
  # priors
  for (i in 1:2){
    beta[i] ~ dnorm(0, .00001)
  }
  sigma ~ dunif(0, 10)
  
  # likelihood
  mu = X %*% beta
  prec.mat <- inverse(sigma^2 * y.I) 
  y ~ dmnorm(mu, prec.mat)
  epsilon <- y - mu
}
", fill = TRUE)
sink()
} # Extra bracket needed only for R markdown files
data = list(
  y = as.double(dat$y[k]),
  X = X[k,],
  y.I = diag(length(k))
)

Aspatial model redux

We now want to add spatial structure into that is not accounted for by the covariates. Here again is the joint distribution using the multivariate normal:

\[\begin{align} \big[\beta_{1}, \beta_{2}, \sigma, \varsigma, \phi \mid \mathbf{y}\big] & \propto \textrm{multivariate normal}\big(\mathbf{y} \mid \boldsymbol{\mu},\boldsymbol{\Sigma} + \sigma^{2}I\big) \textrm{normal}\big(\beta_{1} \mid 0, 1E5 \big) \textrm{normal}\big(\beta_{2} \mid 0, 1E5 \big)\\ & \times \textrm{uniform}\big(\sigma \mid 0, 10\big)\textrm{uniform}\big(\varsigma \mid 0, 10\big)\textrm{uniform}\big(\phi \mid 20000, 80000\big)\\ \boldsymbol{\mu}&=\mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta} \end{align}\]

except this time the variance covariance matrix now has two sources of error, the original uncorrelated error captured by \(\sigma^2I\) and the new exponentially correlated errors from \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\) such that:

\[\boldsymbol{\Sigma} = \varsigma^{2}\textrm{exp}\Big(\frac{-d_{i,j}}{\phi}\Big) = \begin{bmatrix} \varsigma^{2} & \varsigma^{2}e^{-\frac{d_{1,2}}{\phi}} & \varsigma^{2}e^{-\frac{d_{1,3}}{\phi}} & \dots & \varsigma^{2}e^{-\frac{d_{1,875}}{\phi}} \\ \varsigma^{2}e^{-\frac{d_{2,1}}{\phi}} & \varsigma^{2} & \varsigma^{2}e^{-\frac{d_{2,3}}{\phi}} & \dots & \varsigma^{2}e^{-\frac{d_{2,875}}{\phi}} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ \varsigma^{2}e^{-\frac{d_{875,1}}{\phi}} & \varsigma^{2}e^{-\frac{d_{875,2}}{\phi}} & \varsigma^{2}e^{-\frac{d_{875,3}}{\phi}} & \dots & \varsigma^{2} \end{bmatrix}_{\,\,875\times 875} \]

1. Study the code below that simulates data using the above model until you understand it. You may need to refer to the lecture notes. We get a vector of new \(\epsilon\)s using rmvnorm, which returns a single vector of length 875 centered on 0. Sigma is calculated above to reflect spatial autocorelation. Now we create spatially structured data by adding these new spatially structured random variables to the unstructured ys.

D <- as.matrix(dist(utgrid.locs))
sigma_structured <- 2
phi <- 50000
Sigma <- sigma_structured * exp(-D / phi)
epsilon_spatial <- as.vector(rmvnorm(1, matrix(0, n, 1), Sigma, method = "chol"))
dat$y_structured <- dat$y + epsilon_spatial
par(mfrow = c(1, 3))
plot(seq(0, max(D),, 20), sigma_structured * exp(-seq(0, max(D),, 20) / phi), type = "o", 
     ylab = "cov", xlab = "distance")
image(matrix(epsilon_spatial, length(xg), length(yg)), x = xg, y = yg, main = "epsilon spatial",
      col = rev(rainbow(100, start = 0, end = .7)), xlab = "easting", ylab = "northing",
      cex.main = .8, cex.axis = .7, xlim = c(min(xg), max(xg)), ylim = c(min(yg), max(yg)))
points(ut.utm@coords, type = "l", lwd = 3)
image(matrix(dat$y_structured, length(xg), length(yg)), x = xg, y = yg, main = "y structured + spatial",
      col = rev(rainbow(100, start = 0, end = .7)), xlab = "easting", ylab = "northing",
      cex.main = .8, cex.axis = .7, xlim = c(min(xg), max(xg)), ylim = c(min(yg), max(yg)))
points(ut.utm@coords, type = "l", lwd = 3)

Spatial model

Modify the aspatial model to account for spatial dependence in the residuals. How many new parameters must be predicted? Again, we give you the data and the inits to accelerate things.

inits = list(
  list(
    beta = c(.8, -.8),
    sigma = c(.02, 1),
    phi = 50000)
)

data = list(
  y = as.double(dat$y_structured[k]),
  X = X[k,],
  D = matrix(D[k, k], nrow = length(k), ncol = length(k)),
  y.I = diag(length(k))
)

1. Time to write the spatial model. Use the priors we provide above to save time and remember it is critical that your code contains a derived quantity for the residuals, i.e., \(\epsilon_i=y_i-\mu_i\). Again, include code for a posterior predictive check for the coefficient of variation.


{
sink("SpatialJAGS.R")
cat("
model{
  # priors
  for (i in 1:2) {
    beta[i] ~ dnorm(0,.00001)
  }
  sigma[1] ~ dunif(0, 10) 
  sigma[2] ~ dunif(0, 10)
  phi ~ dunif(20000, 80000)

  # likelihood  
  mu = X %*% beta
  for (i in 1:length(y)){
    for (j in 1:length(y)){
      Cov.mat[i, j] <- sigma[2] * exp(-D[i,j] / phi)
    }
  }
  prec.mat <- inverse(Cov.mat + sigma[1]^2 * y.I)
  y ~ dmnorm(mu, prec.mat) 
  y.new ~ dmnorm(mu, prec.mat) 
  epsilon <- y - mu

  # derived quantities
  cv.y <- sd(y[]) / mean(y[])
  cv.y.new <- sd(y.new[]) / mean(y.new[])
  pvalue.cv <- step(cv.y.new - cv.y)   

}
",fill=TRUE)
sink()
}

2. Run the model in JAGS with a single chain and assess convergence.


jm_c = jags.model("SpatialJAGS.R", n.adapt = n.adapt, n.chains = 1, inits = inits, data = data)
